[{"id":1,"section_id":1,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":""},{"id":2,"section_id":2,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Documentation and Metadata","description":""},{"id":3,"section_id":3,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Storage and Backup","description":""},{"id":4,"section_id":4,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Preservation","description":""},{"id":5,"section_id":5,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Sharing and Reuse","description":""},{"id":6,"section_id":6,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":""},{"id":7,"section_id":7,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Study Overview","description":"The section is to provide overview of study taken from Protocol, ethics application or other document as appropriate. "},{"id":8,"section_id":8,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":"This section is an overview of the data collection tasks performed by data management. "},{"id":9,"section_id":9,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Study Monitoring","description":""},{"id":10,"section_id":10,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Storage and Tracking","description":""},{"id":11,"section_id":11,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Entry","description":""},{"id":12,"section_id":12,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Handling","description":""},{"id":13,"section_id":13,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Quality Control","description":""},{"id":14,"section_id":15,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Coding","description":""},{"id":15,"section_id":16,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Sharing and Delivery","description":""},{"id":16,"section_id":17,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Preservation and Archiving","description":""},{"id":17,"section_id":18,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":""},{"id":18,"section_id":36,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Providing Intelligent Access","description":"<p>Identify how intelligent access will be provided for the data.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":19,"section_id":43,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"2 Sources of Data and Any Special Code or Software","description":"<p>Obtain a description of the data sources to be used.</p>"},{"id":20,"section_id":44,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"3 Restrictions Around the Data","description":"Identify any restrictions on the data that will limit how others might have access to the data."},{"id":21,"section_id":45,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"4 Data Repository","description":"Determine if the data will be deposited in an existing data repository and the type of arrangements associated with this."},{"id":22,"section_id":46,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"5 - Providing Intelligent Access","description":"Identify how intelligent access will be provided for the data. "},{"id":23,"section_id":47,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"6 Data Citation","description":"Determine a proper citation for the data used in this project."},{"id":24,"section_id":48,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":""},{"id":25,"section_id":50,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Documentation and Metadata","description":""},{"id":26,"section_id":52,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Storage and Backup","description":""},{"id":27,"section_id":53,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Preservation","description":""},{"id":28,"section_id":54,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Data Sharing and Reuse","description":""},{"id":29,"section_id":55,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:53 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":""},{"id":30,"section_id":56,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":"This section addresses data collection issues such as data types, file formats, naming conventions, and data organisation – factors that will improve the usability of your data and contribute to the success of your project."},{"id":31,"section_id":57,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","title":"Documentation and Metadata","description":"Because data are rarely self-explanatory, all research data should be accompanied by metadata (information that describes the data according to community best practices).  Metadata standards vary across disciplines, but generally state who created the data and when, how the data were created, their quality, accuracy, and precision, as well as other features necessary to facilitate data discovery, understanding and reuse. </br>Any restrictions on use of the data must be explained in the metadata, along with information on how to obtain approved access to the data, where possible."},{"id":32,"section_id":58,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","title":"Storage and Backup","description":"Planning how research data will be stored and backed up throughout and beyond a research project is critical in ensuring data security and integrity. Appropriate storage and backup not only helps protect research data from catastrophic losses (due to hardware and software failures, viruses, hackers, natural disasters, human error, etc.), but also facilitates appropriate access by current and future researchers."},{"id":33,"section_id":59,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","title":"Preservation","description":"Data preservation will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future. In some circumstances, it may be desirable to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to keep only selected or final data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews)."},{"id":34,"section_id":60,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","title":"Sharing and Reuse","description":"Most Canadian research funding agencies now have policies requiring research data to be shared upon publication of the research results or within a reasonable period of time. While data sharing contributes to the visibility and impact of research, it has to be balanced with the legitimate desire of researchers to maximise their research outputs before releasing their data. Equally important is the need to protect the privacy of respondents and to properly handle sensitive data."},{"id":35,"section_id":61,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":"Data management focuses on the 'what' and 'how' of operationally supporting data across the research lifecycle.  Data stewardship focuses on 'who' is responsible for ensuring that data management happens. A large project, for example, will involve multiple data stewards. The Principal Investigator should identify at the beginning of a project all of the people who will have responsibilities for data management tasks during and after the project."},{"id":36,"section_id":62,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","title":"Ethics and Legal Compliance","description":"Researchers and their teams need to be aware of the policies and processes, both ethical and legal, to which their research data management must comply. Protection of respondent privacy is of paramount importance and informs many data management practices.  In their data management plan, researchers must state how they will prepare, store, share, and archive the data in a way that ensures participant information is protected, throughout the research lifecycle, from disclosure, harmful use, or inappropriate linkages with other personal data.</br>It's recognized that there may be cases where certain data and metadata cannot be made public for various policy or legal reasons, however, the default position should be that all research data and metadata are public."},{"id":37,"section_id":56,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","title":"Collecte de données","description":"Cette section traite des questions relatives à la collecte de données comme les types de données, les formats de fichier, les conventions d'appellation et l'organisation des données – des facteurs qui amélioreront la facilité d'utilisation de vos données et contribueront au succès de votre projet."},{"id":38,"section_id":57,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","title":"Documentation et métadonnées","description":"Les données sont rarement explicites, c'est pourquoi toutes les données de recherche doivent être accompagnées de métadonnées (des renseignements qui décrivent les données selon les meilleures pratiques de la communauté). Les normes de métadonnées varient d'une discipline à l'autre, mais elles indiquent généralement la personne qui a créé les données, quand et comment elles ont été créées, leur qualité, exactitude et précision ainsi que d'autres caractéristiques nécessaires pour faciliter la découverte, la compréhension et la réutilisation des données. </br>Toute restriction concernant l'utilisation des données doit être expliquée dans les métadonnées et, dans la mesure du possible, des renseignements doivent être fournis sur la façon d'obtenir un accès approuvé aux données."},{"id":39,"section_id":58,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","title":"Stockage et sauvegarde","description":"Il est essentiel de planifier la façon dont les données de recherche seront stockées et sauvegardées tout au long d'un projet de recherche et au-delà afin d'assurer la sécurité et l'intégrité des données. Le stockage et la sauvegarde appropriés aident non seulement à protéger les données de recherche contre des pertes catastrophiques (en raison de défaillances du logiciel et du matériel, de virus, de pirates informatiques, de catastrophes naturelles, d'erreurs humaines, etc.), mais y facilitent également l'accès approprié par les chercheurs actuels et futurs."},{"id":40,"section_id":59,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","title":"Conservation","description":"La conservation des données dépendra de la valeur de réutilisation potentielle, s'il faut conserver ou détruire les données, et des ressources requises pour organiser de façon appropriée les données et s'assurer qu'elles demeurent utilisables dans le futur. Dans certains cas, il peut être souhaitable de conserver toutes les versions des données (p. ex. les données brutes, traitées, analysées, définitives), mais dans d'autres cas, il peut être préférable de conserver uniquement les données sélectionnées ou définitives (p. ex. transcriptions au lieu d'entrevues sonores)."},{"id":41,"section_id":60,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:13 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:13 UTC","title":"Partage et réutilisation","description":"Plusieurs organismes subventionnaires canadiens ont maintenant des politiques exigeant que les données de recherche soient rendues accessibles au moment de la publication des résultats de la recherche ou à l'intérieur d'un délai raisonnable. Si le partage des données contribue à la visibilité et à l'impact de la recherche, il faut aussi tenir compte du souhait des chercheurs de publier un maximum de publications avant de diffuser les données. Également d'importance est le besoin de protéger la vie privée des répondants et de traiter de façon appropriée les données sensibles. "},{"id":42,"section_id":61,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:13 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:13 UTC","title":"Responsabilités et ressources","description":"La notion de gestion des données fait référence au « quoi » et au « comment » des opérations de gestion liées aux données tout au long du cycle de vie du projet. La notion de gérance des données met de son côté l'accent sur « qui » est responsable de s'assurer que cette gestion des données est faite. Un gros projet de recherche aura par exemple plusieurs personnes responsables.  Le chercheur principal doit déterminer au début du projet quelles personnes dans l'équipe auront des responsabilités en matière de gestion des données pendant et après le projet."},{"id":43,"section_id":62,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:13 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:13 UTC","title":"Conformité aux lois et à l'éthique","description":"Les chercheurs et leurs équipes doivent connaître les politiques et les processus, éthiques et juridiques, auxquels leur gestion des données de recherche doit se conformer. La protection de la vie privée du répondant revêt une importance capitale et façonne plusieurs pratiques en matière de gestion des données. Dans leur plan de gestion des données, les chercheurs doivent indiquer la façon dont ils prépareront, stockeront, partageront et archiveront les données de façon à s'assurer que les renseignements sur les participants sont protégés tout au long du cycle de vie de la recherche contre la divulgation, l'utilisation préjudiciable ou les liens inappropriés avec d'autres données personnelles.</br>On reconnait qu'il peut y avoir des cas où certaines données et métadonnées ne peuvent pas être rendues publiques en raison de politiques ou de considérations légales. Toutefois, la position par défaut doit être que toutes les données et métadonnées de recherche sont publiques."},{"id":44,"section_id":75,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:15:56 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:15:56 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":"<p>This section addresses data collection issues such as data types, file formats, naming conventions, and data organisation &ndash; factors that will improve the usability of your data and contribute to the success of your project.</p>"},{"id":45,"section_id":76,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:25:23 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:25:23 UTC","title":"Documentation and Metadata","description":"<p>Data are rarely self-explanatory, so information about how to interpret research data and the context in which they were collected is key. This &lsquo;data about data&rsquo;, or metadata, ensures data can be understood, analysed, shared, reused, and preserved. Many disciplines have metadata standards that ensure data can be interpreted and compared across projects and fields. The Social Sciences, for instance, use the internationally-accepted Data Documentation Initiative (DDI) standard.<br />Where there are restrictions on the use of the data, the reasons for these restrictions must be explained in the metadata. Information must describe how to gain controlled access to the data if possible (e.g., contact information, access terms, access agreement templates, data request forms, etc.).</p>"},{"id":46,"section_id":77,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:41:07 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:41:07 UTC","title":"Storage and Backup","description":"<p>Planning how research data will be stored and backed up throughout and beyond a research project is critical in ensuring data security and integrity. Appropriate storage and backup not only helps protect research data from catastrophic losses (due to hardware and software failures, viruses, hackers, natural disasters, human error, etc.), but also facilitates appropriate access by current and future researchers.</p>"},{"id":47,"section_id":78,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:50:15 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:50:15 UTC","title":"Data Preservation","description":"<p>Data preservation will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future. In some circumstances, it may be desirable to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to keep only selected or final data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).</p>"},{"id":48,"section_id":79,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:55:52 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 18:02:19 UTC","title":"Data Sharing and Reuse","description":"<p>Most Canadian research funding agencies now have policies requiring research data to be shared upon publication of the research results or within a reasonable period of time. While data sharing contributes to the visibility and impact of research, it has to be balanced with the legitimate desire of researchers to maximise their research outputs before releasing their data. Equally important is the need to protect the privacy of respondents and to properly handle sensitive data.</p>"},{"id":49,"section_id":80,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:03:05 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 18:07:14 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":"<p>Data management focuses on the &lsquo;what&rsquo; and &lsquo;how&rsquo; of operationally supporting data across the research lifecycle. Data stewardship focuses on &lsquo;who&rsquo; is responsible for ensuring that data management happens. A large project, for example, will involve multiple data stewards. The Principal Investigator should identify at the beginning of a project all of the people who will have responsibilities for data management tasks during and after the project.</p>"},{"id":50,"section_id":81,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:08:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 18:08:12 UTC","title":"Ethics and Legal Compliance","description":"<p>Researchers and their teams need to be aware of the policies and processes, both ethical and legal, to which their research data management must comply. Protection of respondent privacy is of paramount importance and informs many data management practices. In their data management plan, researchers must state how they will prepare, store, share, and archive the data in a way that ensures participant information is protected throughout the research lifecycle from disclosure, harmful use, or inappropriate linkages with other personal data. <br />It&rsquo;s recognized that there may be cases where certain data and metadata cannot be made public for various policy or legal reasons, however, the default position should be that all research data and metadata are public.</p>"},{"id":51,"section_id":82,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-01-08 17:33:01 UTC","updated_at":"2016-01-08 17:39:25 UTC","title":"Test Section 1","description":""},{"id":52,"section_id":83,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-02-18 21:14:38 UTC","updated_at":"2016-02-18 21:14:38 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":53,"section_id":84,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-02-18 21:15:08 UTC","updated_at":"2016-02-18 21:15:08 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":54,"section_id":85,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-02-18 21:16:03 UTC","updated_at":"2016-02-18 21:16:03 UTC","title":"uOttawa Test2 Section1","description":"<p>Test1</p>"},{"id":55,"section_id":86,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-02-18 21:17:14 UTC","updated_at":"2016-02-18 21:17:14 UTC","title":"uOttwa Test2 Section2","description":""},{"id":57,"section_id":88,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-03-07 17:17:47 UTC","updated_at":"2016-03-07 17:17:47 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":58,"section_id":89,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-03-07 17:19:20 UTC","updated_at":"2016-03-07 17:19:20 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":59,"section_id":90,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-03-07 17:26:36 UTC","updated_at":"2016-03-07 17:26:36 UTC","title":"Initial planning","description":"<p>Type of data, consent form etc.</p>"},{"id":60,"section_id":91,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-03-11 19:57:17 UTC","updated_at":"2016-03-11 19:57:17 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":61,"section_id":92,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-03-11 19:59:36 UTC","updated_at":"2016-03-11 19:59:36 UTC","title":"More planning","description":"<p>Testing versions</p>"},{"id":63,"section_id":94,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-04-19 17:37:11 UTC","updated_at":"2016-04-19 17:37:11 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":64,"section_id":95,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-04-19 17:38:11 UTC","updated_at":"2016-04-19 17:38:11 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":65,"section_id":96,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-06-03 16:14:34 UTC","updated_at":"2016-06-03 16:14:34 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":66,"section_id":97,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-06-03 16:17:03 UTC","updated_at":"2016-06-03 16:17:03 UTC","title":"Test DMP question v1","description":""},{"id":67,"section_id":98,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-06-03 16:40:29 UTC","updated_at":"2016-06-03 16:40:29 UTC","title":"nuts and bolts","description":""},{"id":68,"section_id":99,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-06-28 17:09:20 UTC","updated_at":"2016-06-28 17:09:20 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":69,"section_id":100,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 20:41:45 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:48:45 UTC","title":"Sharing and Reuse","description":""},{"id":70,"section_id":101,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:35:01 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:35:01 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":""},{"id":71,"section_id":102,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:46:38 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:46:38 UTC","title":"Storage and Backup","description":""},{"id":72,"section_id":103,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:50:05 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:50:05 UTC","title":"Preservation","description":""},{"id":73,"section_id":104,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:50:53 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:50:53 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":""},{"id":74,"section_id":105,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:52:10 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:52:10 UTC","title":"Ethics and Legal Compliance","description":""},{"id":75,"section_id":106,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-23 22:18:06 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-26 23:08:07 UTC","title":"Data Collection, Processing and Methodology","description":""},{"id":76,"section_id":107,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 16:19:41 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 16:19:41 UTC","title":"Documentation and Metadata","description":""},{"id":77,"section_id":108,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 19:46:01 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 19:46:01 UTC","title":"Ethics and legal compliance","description":"<p>Describe any Copyright or Intellectual Property (IP) in the material that will be generated and/or collected. Example:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>MSc., Ph.D. Student &lt;insert name&gt;</li>\r\n<li>University of Manitoba (IP has been assigned to the University)</li>\r\n<li>Joint ownership, External party</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":78,"section_id":109,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 19:53:06 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 19:53:06 UTC","title":"Storage and backup","description":""},{"id":79,"section_id":110,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 21:35:44 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 21:36:11 UTC","title":"Selection and Preservation","description":"<p>What data must be retained/destroyed for contractual, legal, or regulatory purposes? How long will you retain it for? How much backup space is needed? Reference Sections 3.1, 4 and 5 to include in your plan.</p>"},{"id":80,"section_id":111,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 21:37:04 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 21:37:04 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":""},{"id":81,"section_id":112,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-10-14 15:33:39 UTC","updated_at":"2016-10-14 15:33:39 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":82,"section_id":113,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-10-14 15:41:37 UTC","updated_at":"2016-10-14 15:41:37 UTC","title":"Section 2 testing","description":"<p>Will this save?</p>"},{"id":83,"section_id":114,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-10-14 15:41:54 UTC","updated_at":"2016-10-14 15:41:54 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":84,"section_id":115,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-11-10 19:19:51 UTC","updated_at":"2016-11-10 19:19:51 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":85,"section_id":116,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-11-10 20:00:09 UTC","updated_at":"2016-11-10 20:00:09 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":86,"section_id":117,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-11-10 20:15:20 UTC","updated_at":"2016-11-10 20:15:20 UTC","title":"section 2","description":""},{"id":87,"section_id":118,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:36:53 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 12:44:13 UTC","title":"Data Summary","description":""},{"id":88,"section_id":119,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:42:57 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 12:49:06 UTC","title":"Data Quality","description":""},{"id":89,"section_id":120,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:49:22 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-18 22:18:47 UTC","title":"Metadata Standards","description":""},{"id":90,"section_id":121,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:54:41 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 12:54:41 UTC","title":"Preservation/Access","description":""},{"id":91,"section_id":122,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:11:34 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:11:34 UTC","title":"Ethics and Legal Compliance","description":""},{"id":92,"section_id":123,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:24:15 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:24:15 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":""},{"id":93,"section_id":124,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-07-21 23:02:03 UTC","updated_at":"2017-07-21 23:02:03 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":95,"section_id":126,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2017-11-01 20:15:07 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-01 20:15:07 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":96,"section_id":127,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2017-11-01 20:19:38 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-01 20:19:38 UTC","title":"Section 2","description":"<p>ceci est la 2e section</p>"},{"id":97,"section_id":128,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-14 22:20:43 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-14 22:20:43 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":98,"section_id":129,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-23 21:40:55 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-23 21:40:55 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":99,"section_id":130,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-23 21:47:24 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-23 21:47:24 UTC","title":"This plan is based on: ","description":"<p>The example template used as the basis of this template.</p>"},{"id":100,"section_id":131,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-23 21:57:22 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-23 22:36:33 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":"<p>This section addresses issues including data types, file formats, naming conventions, and data organization. Describing each of these factors will improve the usability of your data.</p>"},{"id":101,"section_id":132,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-26 17:14:12 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-26 17:14:12 UTC","title":"Documentation and Metadata","description":"<p>Descriptive information added to each individual data item is key to its discovery and access. This description includes how to interpret the data and the context in which it is collected. The description, 'data about data' or metadata, ensures data can be understood, analysed, shared, reused, and preserved. Many disciplines have metadata standards that ensure data can be interpreted and compared across projects and fields. For example, the Data Documentation Initiative (DDI) standard is an internationally-accepted metadata standard in the social sciences.</p>\r\n<p>Where there are restrictions on the use or access to the data, the reasons for these restriction must be explained in the metadata. Information must describe how to obtain access to the data if possible (e.g. contact information, access terms, access agreement templates, data request forms etc.)</p>"},{"id":102,"section_id":133,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-26 21:33:06 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-26 21:33:06 UTC","title":"Storage and Backup","description":"<p>Planning how research data will be stored and backed up during and after a project is an essential piece of data security and integrity. Appropriate storage and backup protects against loss (from hardware/software fails, viruses, hackers, natural diasters, human error etc.), and facilitates appropriate access, as per regulatory and/or grant stipulations, by current and future researchers.</p>"},{"id":103,"section_id":134,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:02:57 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 18:24:35 UTC","title":"Project Information","description":"<p>The section is to provide an overview of the research project taken from project planning documents, ethics application or other document as appropriate. It includes questions regarding security, privacy and ethics and legal compliance.</p>"},{"id":104,"section_id":135,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:20:49 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-05 16:24:23 UTC","title":"Plan and acquire","description":"<p>The section is to provide an overview of the data that is to be collected, acquired and/or generated and addresses questions pertaining to security, privacy and ethics and legal compliance. The data management plan should consider the origins of the data and ensure that proper procedures to manage the data are in place.</p>"},{"id":105,"section_id":136,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:32:58 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-05 16:23:51 UTC","title":"Describe and manage quality","description":"<p>The section addresses issues such as standards, naming conventions, and data organisation &ndash; factors that will improve the usability of your data and contribute to the success of your project.</p>"},{"id":106,"section_id":137,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:34:14 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:34:14 UTC","title":"Data Preservation","description":"<p>Considerations of data preservation include: potential reuse value; regulatory and/or grant obligations to retain or destroy data;&nbsp;and resources required to both properly curate the data as well as ensure it is reusable into the future. Depending on the circumstances, all versions of the data may be preserved (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final); in others, only the selected or final data may be need to be preserved (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).</p>"},{"id":107,"section_id":138,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:58:05 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-05 16:40:29 UTC","title":"Storage, Backup and preservation","description":"<p>The section describes&nbsp;how research data will be stored and backed up throughout and beyond a research project. Appropriate storage and backup not only helps protect research data, but also facilitates appropriate access by current and future project team members and researchers. Data preservation will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future. In some circumstances, it may be desirable to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to keep only selected or final data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).</p>"},{"id":108,"section_id":139,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:51:50 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-05 18:19:57 UTC","title":"Data sharing and access","description":"<p>The section describes how data will be shared, internally and externally, and rendered accessible. &ldquo;Open&rdquo; principles are to be applied where appropriate and to the greatest extent possible.</p>"},{"id":109,"section_id":140,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 18:17:30 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 18:17:30 UTC","title":"Data Access and Reuse","description":"<p>The majority of major funders, Canadian and iinternationally, now require research data to be shared and/or publically accessible either immediately upon publication or within a certain period of time.&nbsp;Weighing the benefits of data sharing, such as increased visibility and research impact, together with legitimate need to protect competitive potential and privacy/confidentiality of the data,&nbsp;are all considerations in this section.</p>"},{"id":110,"section_id":141,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 21:51:12 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 21:51:12 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":"<p>This section is about data stewardship: the 'who' that is responsible for ensuring that data management happens. For example, a large project will involve multiple data stewards. The Principle Investigator should identify at the beginning of a project all of the people who will have responsibilities for data management tasks throughout the research cycle and beyond.</p>"},{"id":111,"section_id":142,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-28 16:50:21 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-28 16:50:21 UTC","title":"Ethics and Legal Compliance","description":"<p>All those involved in research have an obligation to be knowledgeable of the policies and processes, both ethical and legal, to which their research data management must comply. Assurance of confidentiality and privacy of human subject data is imparative and informs many data management practices. As part of a data management plan, researchers must state how they will prepare, store, share, and archive their data that ensures human subject data is secure throughout the research lifecycle from disclosure, harmful use, or inappropriate linkages with other personal data. To that end, while it is acknowledged that there are circumstances where some data and metadata cannot be made publically accessible for policy and legal reasons, the default position is that access to all research data and metadata are public.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":113,"section_id":144,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-03-02 01:41:51 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-02 01:41:51 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":114,"section_id":145,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-05-28 19:00:50 UTC","updated_at":"2018-05-28 19:00:50 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":116,"section_id":147,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:22:02 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-12 14:22:02 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":""},{"id":117,"section_id":148,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:24:55 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-12 14:24:55 UTC","title":"Preservation","description":""},{"id":119,"section_id":150,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:26:30 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-12 14:26:30 UTC","title":"Sharing and Reuse","description":""},{"id":120,"section_id":151,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:27:08 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-13 15:02:09 UTC","title":"Restrictions","description":""},{"id":121,"section_id":152,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-13 15:09:38 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-13 15:09:38 UTC","title":"Security","description":""},{"id":122,"section_id":153,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:08:38 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:08:38 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":123,"section_id":154,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:15:25 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:15:25 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":125,"section_id":156,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:19:34 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:24:30 UTC","title":"Collecte de données","description":""},{"id":126,"section_id":157,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:20:34 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:20:34 UTC","title":"Documentation et métadonnées","description":""},{"id":127,"section_id":158,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:21:22 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:21:22 UTC","title":"Stockage et sauvegarde","description":""},{"id":128,"section_id":159,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:21:43 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:21:43 UTC","title":"Conservation","description":""},{"id":129,"section_id":160,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:22:08 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:22:08 UTC","title":"Partage et réutilisation","description":""},{"id":130,"section_id":161,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:23:22 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:23:22 UTC","title":"Responsabilités et ressources","description":""},{"id":131,"section_id":162,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:23:49 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:23:49 UTC","title":"Conformité aux lois et à l'éthique","description":""},{"id":135,"section_id":180,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 14:58:23 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 14:58:49 UTC","title":"Collecte de données","description":""},{"id":136,"section_id":181,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 14:59:03 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 14:59:03 UTC","title":"Documentation et métadonnées","description":""},{"id":137,"section_id":182,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 14:59:17 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 14:59:17 UTC","title":"Stockage et sauvegarde","description":""},{"id":138,"section_id":183,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 14:59:32 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 14:59:32 UTC","title":"Conservation","description":""},{"id":139,"section_id":184,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 14:59:46 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 14:59:46 UTC","title":"Partage et réutilisation","description":""},{"id":140,"section_id":185,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:00:14 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:00:14 UTC","title":"Responsabilités et ressources","description":""},{"id":141,"section_id":186,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:00:27 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:00:27 UTC","title":"Conformité aux lois et à l'éthique","description":""},{"id":142,"section_id":181,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 20:07:26 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 20:07:26 UTC","title":"Documentation et métadonnées","description":""},{"id":143,"section_id":180,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:00:32 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:00:32 UTC","title":"Collecte de données","description":""},{"id":144,"section_id":182,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:00:57 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:00:57 UTC","title":"Stockage et sauvegarde","description":""},{"id":145,"section_id":183,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:26:46 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:26:46 UTC","title":"Conservation","description":""},{"id":146,"section_id":184,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:27:57 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:27:57 UTC","title":"Partage et réutilisation","description":""},{"id":147,"section_id":185,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:29:04 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:29:04 UTC","title":"Responsabilités et ressources","description":""},{"id":148,"section_id":186,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:30:20 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:30:20 UTC","title":"Conformité aux lois et à l'éthique","description":""},{"id":149,"section_id":194,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 16:32:41 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 16:51:23 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This section addresses data collection issues such as data types, file formats, naming conventions, and data organisation &ndash; factors that will improve the usability of your data and contribute to the success of your project.</span></p>"},{"id":151,"section_id":196,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 16:57:37 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:24:47 UTC","title":"Documentation and Metadata","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Because data are rarely self-explanatory, all research data should be accompanied by metadata (information that describes the data according to community best practices). Metadata standards vary across disciplines, but generally state who created the data and when, how the data were created, their quality, accuracy, and precision, as well as other features necessary to facilitate data discovery, understanding and reuse. Any restrictions on use of the data must be explained in the metadata, along with information on how to obtain approved access to the data, where possible.</span></p>"},{"id":152,"section_id":197,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:01:55 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:17:54 UTC","title":"Storage and Backup","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Planning how research data will be stored and backed up throughout and beyond a research project is critical in ensuring data security and integrity. Appropriate storage and backup not only helps protect research data from catastrophic losses (due to hardware and software failures, viruses, hackers, natural disasters, human error, etc.), but also facilitates appropriate access by current and future researchers </span></p>"},{"id":153,"section_id":198,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:12:21 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:17:09 UTC","title":"Sensitive Data and Legal Compliance","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Researchers and their teams need to be aware of the policies and processes, both ethical and legal, to which their research data must comply. Protection of sensitive data&nbsp;is of paramount importance and informs many data management practices. In a&nbsp;data management plan, researchers must state how they will prepare, store, share, and archive the data in a way that ensures all sensitive data involving personal information, intellectual property rights, commercial concerns, and other key ethical issues are protected throughout the research lifecycle from disclosure, harmful use, or inappropriate linkages with other identifying data.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is recognized that there may be cases where certain data cannot be made public for various policy or legal reasons. In these instances, consider whether de-identifying your sensitive data is possible and would allow safe sharing. Also consider publishing metadata, without making the data itself openly accessible, which enables restrictions and conditions to be placed on accessing the data.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span></p>"},{"id":154,"section_id":199,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:17:02 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:17:02 UTC","title":"Preservation","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data preservation will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future. In some circumstances, it may be desirable to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to keep only selected or final data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).</span></p>"},{"id":155,"section_id":200,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:22:35 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:22:35 UTC","title":"Sharing and Reuse","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Most Canadian research funding agencies and journal publishers now have policies requiring research data to be shared upon publication of the research results or within a reasonable period of time. While data sharing contributes to the visibility and impact of research, it has to be balanced with the legitimate desire of researchers to maximise their research outputs before releasing their data. Equally important is the need to protect the privacy of respondents and to properly handle sensitive data.</span></p>"},{"id":156,"section_id":201,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:26:20 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:09:08 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data management focuses on the 'what' and 'how' of operationally supporting data across the research lifecycle. Data stewardship focuses on 'who' is responsible for ensuring that data management happens. A large project, for example, will involve multiple data stewards. The Principal Investigator should identify at the beginning of a project all of the people who will have responsibilities for data management tasks during and after the project.</span></p>"},{"id":157,"section_id":202,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:21:12 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-20 15:44:21 UTC","title":"Data collection","description":"<p>This section addresses data collection considerations to ensure that your data is safely and securely stored and efficiently managed.</p>"},{"id":158,"section_id":203,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:24:16 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-20 16:04:04 UTC","title":"Preservation","description":"<p>Data preservation will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future. In some circumstances, it may be desirable to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to keep only selected or final data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).</p>"},{"id":159,"section_id":204,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:25:19 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-05 19:03:54 UTC","title":"Restrictions","description":"<p>Researchers and their teams need to be aware of the policies and processes, both ethical and legal, to which their research data management must comply.</p>"},{"id":160,"section_id":205,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:25:41 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-14 15:53:41 UTC","title":"Sharing and Reuse","description":"<p>The Alliance is committed to supporting the sharing and reuse of data to facilitate new agri-food and rural research. Researchers are encouraged to provide public access to the data deposited where ethical, legal, and commercial requirements allow.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":162,"section_id":207,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:11:44 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:14:03 UTC","title":"Project Information","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This section is to provide an overview of the research project.</span></p>"},{"id":164,"section_id":209,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:26:50 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:26:50 UTC","title":"Data Collection","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This section addresses data collection issues such as data types, file formats, naming conventions, and data organisation &ndash; factors that will improve the usability of your data and contribute to the success of your project.</span></p>"},{"id":165,"section_id":210,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:45:10 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:45:10 UTC","title":"Documentation and Metadata","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Because data are rarely self-explanatory, all research data should be accompanied by metadata (information that describes the data according to community best practices). &nbsp;Metadata standards vary across disciplines, but generally state who created the data and when, how the data were created, their quality, accuracy, and precision, as well as other features necessary to facilitate data discovery, understanding and reuse. Any restrictions on use of the data must be explained in the metadata, along with information on how to obtain approved access to the data, where possible.</span></p>"},{"id":166,"section_id":211,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:50:27 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:50:27 UTC","title":"Storage and Backup","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Planning how research data will be stored and backed up throughout and beyond a research project is critical in ensuring data security and integrity. Appropriate storage and backup not only helps protect research data from catastrophic losses (due to hardware and software failures, viruses, hackers, natural disasters, human error, etc.), but also facilitates appropriate access by current and future researchers.</span></p>"},{"id":167,"section_id":212,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:59:27 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:59:27 UTC","title":"Preservation","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data preservation will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future. In some circumstances, it may be desirable to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to keep only selected or final data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).</span></p>"},{"id":169,"section_id":214,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:08:38 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 17:08:38 UTC","title":"Sharing and Reuse","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Most Canadian research funding agencies now have policies requiring research data to be shared upon publication of the research results or within a reasonable period of time. While data sharing contributes to the visibility and impact of research, it has to be balanced with the legitimate desire of researchers to maximise their research outputs before releasing their data. Equally important is the need to protect the privacy of respondents and to properly handle sensitive data.</span></p>"},{"id":170,"section_id":215,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:19:22 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 17:19:22 UTC","title":"Responsibilities and Resources","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data management focuses on the 'what' and 'how' of operationally supporting data across the research lifecycle. &nbsp;Data stewardship focuses on 'who' is responsible for ensuring that data management happens. A large project, for example, will involve multiple data stewards. The Principal Investigator should identify at the beginning of a project all of the people who will have responsibilities for data management tasks during and after the project.</span></p>"},{"id":171,"section_id":216,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 18:30:47 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 18:30:47 UTC","title":"Ethics and Legal Compliance","description":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Researchers and their teams need to be aware of the policies and processes, both ethical and legal, to which their research data management must comply. Protection of respondent privacy is of paramount importance and informs many data management practices. &nbsp;In their data management plan, researchers must state how they will prepare, store, share, and archive the data in a way that ensures participant information is protected, throughout the research lifecycle, from disclosure, harmful use, or inappropriate linkages with other personal data.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It's recognized that there may be cases where certain data and metadata cannot be made public for various policy or legal reasons, however, the default position should be that all research data and metadata are public.</span></p>"},{"id":172,"section_id":217,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-09 01:52:55 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-09 04:09:16 UTC","title":"Project Information","description":"<p>Project Information</p>"},{"id":173,"section_id":218,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-09 18:16:23 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-09 18:16:23 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":174,"section_id":219,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-09 18:18:37 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-09 18:18:37 UTC","title":"Data collection","description":""},{"id":175,"section_id":220,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 13:50:36 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 13:50:36 UTC","title":"","description":null},{"id":176,"section_id":221,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:00:00 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:00